by the loss of muscle mass and function. It primarily affects the neuromuscular system, leading to various impairments. Sarcopenia primarily affects type II muscle fibres, which are responsible for fast and powerful contractions. The loss of these fibres leads to decreased muscle strength and speed hence there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of maximal contraction force and velocity\u003C/strong\u003E. Sarcopenia contributes to decreased physical function and increased risk of falls in older adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased muscle fibre size\u003C/strong\u003E - Sarcopenia is associated with muscle atrophy, not hypertrophy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased number of type II fibres\u003C/strong\u003E - There is a reduction in type II fibres, not an increase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of type I fibres\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I fibres are less affected in sarcopenia compared to type II fibres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced neuromuscular junction efficiency\u003C/strong\u003E - Sarcopenia is associated with decreased neuromuscular function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sarcopenia is characterised by a loss of muscle mass and strength, particularly affecting type II muscle fibres.","Type II muscle fibres are responsible for fast and powerful contractions, and their loss leads to decreased maximal contraction force and velocity.","Sarcopenia is a common condition in older adults, contributing to decreased physical function and increased risk of falls."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., 